m.","test_description":"Create a lookup table (A1:C5: names, IDs, values). Enter =VLOOKUP(\"name\", A1:C5, 2, 0) and verify the correct ID is returned. Test with non-existent keys to verify an error is returned (not a null or zero). Test with different column indices (2, 3) and verify correct column is returned.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Real failures in range resolution or search would be hidden by mocking the table; the full integration must be tested.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The IF function correctly handles nested conditions (e.g., =IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\")).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Nested IF requires the formula parser/evaluator to recursively parse and evaluate nested expressions correctly. A unit test of IF as a standalone function (with pre-evaluated arguments) would not catch bugs in recursive evaluation of nested expressions or incorrect argument evaluation order.","test_description":"Create A1 and set it to different values (5, 15, 25). For each, enter the nested IF formula and verify the correct result: \"low\", \"medium\", \"high\". Verify the inner IF is evaluated before the outer IF receives its result. Test deeply nested conditions (3+ levels).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Recursive expression evaluation in the formula parser is critical; a unit test of IF logic alone would miss parsing or recursion bugs.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"CONCATENATE joins cell values with the correct separator and handles empty cells by skipping them rather than inserting blank strings.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The function must correctly identify and skip actual empty cells (not mocked). A unit test with mock empty values might not catch bugs in how the 